Number = {10},
Pages = {4021-4053},
Month = {MAY 19},
Abstract = {Cropland use changes significantly impact food security and have been
   extensively studied worldwide, including in China. Accurately mapping
   crop-planting changes in regions with complex cropping patterns remains
   a challenge due to the limitations of existing classification methods.
   In this study, we propose a two-stage classification framework to
   generate 30-m crop maps for monitoring cropland use changes in the
   Guanzhong Plain, China. This framework integrates sample migration and
   cropland mask extraction, with initial grain and non-grain crop masks
   generated from the Random Forest classification. These masks are then
   used in subsequent Random Forest and Decision Tree classifications to
   delineate three types of grain crops and five types of non-grain crops.
   Standard deviation ellipse and gravity centre analysis is used to study
   the spatio-temporal changes of cropland use. The results showed high
   classification performance, with overall accuracy (OA) and kappa
   coefficients exceeding 0.8 and 0.7, respectively. A complex and mixed
   agricultural system has been formed in Guanzhong plain with traditional
   agriculture along the central line of the region and an expanding
   agricultural diversification of non-grain crop cultivation on the
   marginal cropland. The analysis revealed significant shifts in the
   spatial distribution of crops, with grain crops expanding from the
   central and western parts to the entire Guanzhong Plain and clustering
   in the central part, while non-grain crops have expanded from the east
   to the central and western parts. This two-stage classification
   framework offers valuable insights into cropland use changes in the
   Guanzhong Plain and provides essential information for policy -making
   and land use planning.},
