Pages = {573-585},
Abstract = {. To achieve sustainable agricultural development, effective supervision
   of agricultural workers on farms is crucial. Traditional manual
   recording methods suffer from inefficiencies in data management.
   Therefore, automating recordkeeping from video footage represents a
   viable approach to enhancing management efficiency. Addressing the
   challenge of identifying individuals in video, person re-identification
   has emerged as a pivotal research direction in computer vision. This
   article first constructs a unique person re-identification dataset,
   FWreID, tailored specifically to agricultural workers, comprising 4,464
   images of 240 workers. Subsequently, a multi-feature fusion method for
   person re-ID is proposed. This method incorporates a global branch, a
   local branch, and an appearance-contour fusion network. During
   convolutional neural network feature extraction, contour features are
   introduced, and an attention-based fusion network branch is devised to
   enhance the network's ability to capture contour information under
   varying poses. To address occlusion and extract distinctive features
   from individuals, a local feature fusion module is designed,
   contributing to the overall multifeature fusion person re-ID model. By
   integrating global and local information and innovatively designing the
   appearancecontour fusion network, this method overcomes limitations such
   as single-view or missing information typical in traditional approaches,
   significantly improving the accuracy and robustness of agricultural
   worker identification. Experimental results demonstrate that the
   proposed multi-feature fusion method achieves superior performance
   compared to other person re-ID approaches, with rank-1 accuracy of
   95.3\% and mAP of 87.6\% on the FWreID dataset. Furthermore, it shows
   strong robustness with rank-1 accuracies of 95.6\% and 89.1\%, and mAP
   of 88.4\% and 79.4\% on the public datasets Market1501 and
   DukeMTMC-reID, respectively. This advancement is pivotal for digitizing
   and standardizing the management of farm workers by agricultural
   enterprises, thereby promoting the further automation and smart
   transformation of traditional agriculture.},
