Pages = {1094+},
Month = {MAR 10},
Abstract = {Shifting cultivation in North Eastern Region of India is practised along
   the hill slopes by tribes of the region for subsistence living. The
   present study was carried out to examine the dynamics of shifting
   cultivation in relation to slope and elevation in Mokokchung, Teunsang
   and Wokha districts of Nagaland. Temporal Advanced Widefield Sensor data
   of Resources I were used to derive information on the changes and
   spatial extent of shifting cultivation areas in these districts. Slope
   and elevation parameters were derived from Shuttle Radar Thematic Mapper
   data. The study found a change in current shifting cultivation lands to
   regenerating shifting cultivation. All three districts showed an
   increasing trend in regenerating shifting cultivation and decrease in
   current shifting cultivation lands. A shift of cultivation plots towards
   higher elevations was noted. Southern slopes are mostly occupied for
   shifting cultivation by tribal communities in these areas.},
