Number = {4},
Pages = {425-442},
Abstract = {The impact of war and of post-war reconstruction efforts on agriculture
   and forest cover change has been understudied. What happens when
   shifting cultivation -generally seen as one of the main causes of
   deforestation in the tropics -is the dominant agricultural practice?
   Based on the analysis of remote sensing imagery and interviews with
   farmers, we examine the relationship between agricultural practices and
   forest cover change, after the end of the civil war, in two districts of
   the Niassa province, in Mozambique. Our findings support the claims that
   shifting cultivation in Africa is complex, that change may occur in many
   directions and at different rates simultaneously and that tropical
   deforestation is best explained by multiple causes and driving forces
   rather than by single-factor causation. Furthermore, it reveals the
   advantage of combining remote sensing with ethno-agronomic data in the
   study of land use/ cover changes.},
