Pages = {63-76},
Month = {FEB},
Abstract = {This study investigates four decades of socio-economic and environmental
   change in a shifting cultivation landscape in the northern uplands of
   Laos. Historical changes in land cover and land use were analyzed using
   a chronological series of remote sensing data. Impacts of landscape
   change on local livelihoods were investigated in seven villages through
   interviews with various stakeholders. The study reveals that the complex
   mosaics of agriculture and forest patches observed in the study area
   have long constituted key assets for the resilience of local livelihood
   systems in the face of environmental and socio-economic risks. However,
   over the past 20 years, a process of segregating agricultural and forest
   spaces has increased the vulnerability of local land users. This process
   is a direct outcome of policies aimed at increasing national forest
   cover, eradicating shifting cultivation and fostering the emergence of
   more intensive and commercial agricultural practices. We argue that
   agriculture-forest segregation should be buffered in such a way that a
   diversity of livelihood opportunities and economic development pathways
   can be maintained.},
