Year = {2022},
Volume = {26},
Month = {APR},
Abstract = {Tropical deforestation is one of the widely recognised human-induced
   factors responsible for climate change. A clear understanding of the
   trends in forest cover loss hotspots provide baseline information for
   sustainable forest management. This study has utilised Landsat data and
   a novel spatial pattern mining tool to identify trends in forest cover
   loss from 2009 to 2020 in the Araku range of Eastern Ghats, India. This
   study focuses on identifying the annual rate of deforestation and
   significant trends in forest cover loss through statistical techniques.
   Analysis indicates no significant trend in forest loss (P = 0.7 and the
   trend statistic was Z = 0.27; S = 5) during the study period.
   Disturbances in the forest cover are mainly attributed to shifting
   cultivation in the study area. The Emerging hotspot model has found new
   and sporadic hotspots in the Araku range. However, there are no
   intensifying hotspots, historical hotspots and persistent hotspots
   indicate effective management in the majority of the study area. This
   study helps to identify and prioritise deforested areas for monitoring
   and preparing appropriate conservation plans and management strategies.},
