Pages = {563-575},
Month = {JUL},
Abstract = {Malnutrition linked to poor quality diets affects at least 2 billion
   people. Forests, as well as agricultural systems linked to trees, are
   key sources of dietary diversity in rural settings. In the present
   article, we develop conceptual links between diet diversity and forested
   landscape mosaics within the rural tropics. First, we summarize the
   state of knowledge regarding diets obtained from forests, trees, and
   agroforests. We then hypothesize how disturbed secondary forests, edge
   habitats, forest access, and landscape diversity can function in
   bolstering dietary diversity. Taken together, these ideas help us build
   a framework illuminating four pathways (direct, agroecological, energy,
   and market pathways) connecting forested landscapes to diet diversity.
   Finally, we offer recommendations to fill remaining knowledge gaps
   related to diet and forest cover monitoring. We argue that better
   evaluation of the role of land cover complexity will help avoid overly
   simplistic views of food security and, instead, uncover nutritional
   synergies with forest conservation and restoration.},
